AGI - Recent reductions in emissions of small particles, the main cause of global air pollution, have led to an increase in heat in the Earth's climate system.> It reveals a new international study led by Cicero and published on 'Nature Communications Earth &amp; Environment'. Satellite measurements show an imbalance in the Earth's atmosphere > between the heat from the Sun and the amount of earthly energy that escapes into space, with the warmth of the Sun that penetrates to a greater extent. This energy imbalance leads to the accumulation of heat and heating of the earth's surface.
&nbsp;
It is known that anthropic emissions of CO2 and other greenhouse gases have been the main cause of global warming in recent decades and that particle emissions have masked part of this heating. Most of the particles, especially sulphates, reflect sunlight and therefore have a coolant action for the planet. In the last two decades, however, this cooling effect has reversed and now contributes to heating, thanks to the wide measures to improve air quality in many regions of the world.
&nbsp;
In the study, researchers performed simulations using the latest global climate models > and compared their results with satellite measurements of Earth's energy imbalance in the period 2001-2019. The authors found that the recent reduction of anthropogenic particle emissions had to be taken into account to ensure that the models were reasonably consistent with satellite measurements. When scientists hypothesized that particle emissions did not change over time, the simulated heating of the Earth was greatly reduced.

